summary:
"Funny if we both got it wrong, eh? Funny if I did the good thing and you did the bad one, eh?"
Today I was thinking about this...
body:
“Funny if we both got it wrong, eh? Funny if I did the good thing and you did the bad one, eh?”

Today I was thinking about this bit of dialogue in the prologue and it occurred to me that yes, that might be the case, which is ironic and yes, it is funny.

I mean, I don’t know if I’m just stating the obvious and nobody else is saying it because everyone knows (since it’s not very subtle), but in the end knowing the difference between good and evil is what originated humanity as we know it, so it’s arguably a gray action at the least. And then you have Aziraphale’s sword, that apparently became War’s sword, which can be considered a bad thing. So according to that, Crowley would have been spot on when he said that. And I think that’s very interesting.

summary: Sudden realization that I have been pronouncing "Crowley" wrong for YEARS. I always thought the first syllable rhymed with the...
body:
Sudden realization that I have been pronouncing “Crowley” wrong for YEARS. I always thought the first syllable rhymed with the world “owl” but now it’s official that it’s pronounced like “crow” and I can’t deal. My brain won’t accept it. I have heard it pronounced that way in the promos and in interviews but I’ve effectively blocked it out till now. As May 31 nears, I’m slowly coming to terms with the fact.

But I guess, making it pronounced that way makes the whole “Crawly” vs. “Crowley” issue even funnier because they sound very similar.

summary: Fun fact: In the Spanish translation of Good Omens, Aziraphale and Crowley don't hold hands--instead, Crowley high-fives...
body: Fun fact: In the Spanish translation of Good Omens, Aziraphale and Crowley don’t hold hands–instead, Crowley high-fives Aziraphale. Now, I could rant about how that takes away the emotional impact and how it’s possible that they translated it that way so that the readers wouldn’t think They Did An Gay, but honestly the mental image is hilarious and that almost makes up for it.

“Smiling for the cameras, Angel”
